\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Schematic view of the load-bearing backbone and the stages of the rupture process. (a) Two-dimensional view of the backbone subjected to an axial force $F$ along the $y$-axis. Each molecule (gray) is assigned a removal probability $P_{R}$ (Eq.~\ref {eq4}); a molecule is removed when a random number $u\in [0,1]$ satisfies $u<P_{R}$. (b) Progressive damage after some molecules have been removed, represented by red dashed lines. (c) Rupture occurs when a cross-section becomes completely empty (solid lines), eliminating the continuous load path.}}{11}{figure.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig_6}{{6}{11}{Schematic view of the load-bearing backbone and the stages of the rupture process. (a) Two-dimensional view of the backbone subjected to an axial force $F$ along the $y$-axis. Each molecule (gray) is assigned a removal probability $P_{R}$ (Eq.~\ref {eq4}); a molecule is removed when a random number $u\in [0,1]$ satisfies $u<P_{R}$. (b) Progressive damage after some molecules have been removed, represented by red dashed lines. (c) Rupture occurs when a cross-section becomes completely empty (solid lines), eliminating the continuous load path}{figure.6}{}}
\newlabel{eq5}{{5}{11}{}{equation.2.5}{}}
\citation{Bak1987}
\citation{Zapperi1997b}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces (a) Average fraction of removed molecules $\varphi $ versus applied force $F$ for $T_s = 8, 32, 128$, and $8192$. Solid lines are fits to $f(F) = 10^{-3}[\exp (\beta F) -1 + F^{\alpha }]$. (b) and (c) Fitted parameters $\beta $ and $\alpha $ as a function of $T_s$; both decrease reaching a constant for $T_s \geq 512$.}}{12}{figure.7}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig_7}{{7}{12}{(a) Average fraction of removed molecules $\varphi $ versus applied force $F$ for $T_s = 8, 32, 128$, and $8192$. Solid lines are fits to $f(F) = 10^{-3}[\exp (\beta F) -1 + F^{\alpha }]$. (b) and (c) Fitted parameters $\beta $ and $\alpha $ as a function of $T_s$; both decrease reaching a constant for $T_s \geq 512$}{figure.7}{}}
\newlabel{eq6}{{6}{12}{}{equation.2.6}{}}
